WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:04.260
Hi, my name is Meleah Caron, and I went to high school in the Woodlands, Texas.

00:04.260 --> 00:07.820
I attended the Space Settlement Design Competitions at the Johnson Space Center.

00:07.820 --> 00:11.680
I now go to the University of Illinois in Urbana-Champaign, and I'm studying East Asian

00:11.680 --> 00:14.900
Languages and Cultures with a focus on Mandarin Chinese.

00:14.900 --> 00:18.200
The Space Settlement Competitions introduce you to a world that, at least for me as a

00:18.200 --> 00:20.600
student, didn't seem possible.

00:20.600 --> 00:24.560
Space Settlement is science fiction, and it wasn't something that I believed that I,

00:24.560 --> 00:26.480
with no prior knowledge, could contribute to.

00:27.120 --> 00:30.160
But then you get to the event, and you realize that there are topics that you can address

00:30.160 --> 00:34.120
and explore, and the next thing you know, you see your designs reflected in the team's

00:34.120 --> 00:35.280
proposal.

00:35.280 --> 00:39.640
I would recommend the Space Settlement Competitions to anyone who is at all interested in space,

00:39.640 --> 00:44.080
math, engineering, 3D modeling, or pretty much anything in that realm.

00:44.080 --> 00:47.120
But you also have to be someone who is willing to accept criticism.

00:47.120 --> 00:50.760
The single best thing that I got out of the competition was knowing how I reacted to pressure

00:50.760 --> 00:54.240
and stressful conditions, and getting to practice moving through that reaction.

00:54.720 --> 00:58.200
Obviously, the material that you are learning is really cool, and you get to work with all

00:58.200 --> 01:01.880
these mentors who have industry experience, and they're treating you like a real person,

01:01.880 --> 01:06.920
and you're talking about inducing gravity in a space station, or using solar power,

01:06.920 --> 01:10.680
making Gantt charts, and how to direct the team and all of these objectives at the same

01:10.680 --> 01:11.680
time.

01:11.680 --> 01:15.040
I'm confident that every single student leaves the contest having learned something about

01:15.040 --> 01:17.960
space settlement, but there's a bigger takeaway than that.

01:17.960 --> 01:21.600
We may not all become rocket scientists, but everyone will at some point feel the pressure

01:21.600 --> 01:25.320
to get things done in a chaotic situation, and it's really cool to get to practice that

01:25.320 --> 01:28.240
with a group of students who are also feeling that pressure.

01:28.240 --> 01:32.300
I actually really enjoyed the craziness of it all, and I realized that I enjoyed facilitating

01:32.300 --> 01:34.520
a team to accomplish goals together.

01:34.520 --> 01:37.520
That's something that I'm bringing with me into my future career in Army Intelligence.

